{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_13","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"sed -n '1,220p' .workflow/iphone-app-factory/research/design-patterns.md\"","aggregated_output":"# WakeTask iOS Design Pattern Research\n\n## Mobbin access note\n- Mobbin credential presence check: true.\n- Browser inspection reached login/marketing pages, but pattern library routes were session-gated in this environment. This brief therefore uses Apple HIG, competitor research artifacts, and SwiftAIBoilerplatePro DesignSystem references as fallback sources.\n\n## Pattern 1: Trust-first Alarm Setup Wizard\n- Pattern name: Progressive trust-first setup with value and reliability expectations before permissions.\n- Source app or design reference: Alarmy, Nuj, challenge-alarm onboarding/listing narratives, and Apple HIG onboarding and permissions guidance.\n- Why it fits this product: WakeTask competes on reliability under real consequences, so first-run must explain alarm limits, anti-cheat boundaries, and wake-check behavior before users commit.\n- What to adapt into SwiftUI: A short pager with concise copy, urgency mode selector, and explicit permission rationale cards before system prompts.\n- What not to copy: Competitor claims like guaranteed wake-up without evidence; avoid identical step order, visuals, and wording.\n- DesignSystem components or tokens likely to use: SAICard, SAIButton, SAIChip, DSColors.textPrimary, DSColors.surface, DSSpacing, DSTypography, SAIMotion.\n\n## Pattern 2: Mission Stack Composer\n- Pattern name: Configurable challenge stack per alarm.\n- Source app or design reference: Alarmy challenge bundles, Barcode Alarm Clock physical displacement pattern, Reddit math plus movement plus scan workflows.\n- Why it fits this product: Users want anti-autopilot dismissal with control over burden; stack composition gives agency while preserving accountability.\n- What to adapt into SwiftUI: Reorderable mission list, per-mission difficulty chips, time-window exceptions, and a preview of expected dismissal time.\n- What not to copy: Do not replicate exact mission taxonomy, iconography, or challenge microcopy from any single competitor.\n- DesignSystem components or tokens likely to use: SAIListRow, SAIChip, SAITag, SAISectionHeader, DSRadius, DSElevation, DSColors.borderHairline.\n\n## Pattern 3: Post-dismiss Wake Check\n- Pattern name: Delayed verification loop.\n- Source app or design reference: Reddit demand for wake-up checks and relapse prevention; challenge alarm app feedback loops.\n- Why it fits this product: Solves the key failure mode where users complete a task half-awake then return to bed.\n- What to adapt into SwiftUI: After successful dismiss, schedule a short follow-up checkpoint card with configurable window and escalating fallback actions.\n- What not to copy: Avoid punitive escalation and fear-based copy patterns seen in some accountability apps.\n- DesignSystem components or tokens likely to use: SAIToast, SAICard, SAIButton, HapticsClient, DSColors.warning, DSColors.success.\n\n## Pattern 4: Reliability Timeline and Audit Log\n- Pattern name: Explainable reliability history.\n- Source app or design reference: App Store and Reddit trust complaints around missed alarms; Apple HIG clarity and feedback principles.\n- Why it fits this product: Transparent logs reduce anxiety and provide evidence when users question whether the app fired and how they interacted.\n- What to adapt into SwiftUI: Daily timeline with events such as scheduled, fired, snoozed, mission completed, wake-check passed, and wake-check missed.\n- What not to copy: Do not imitate health-chart styling from unrelated apps or expose sensitive behavioral data without clear privacy framing.\n- DesignSystem components or tokens likely to use: SAIListRow, SAISectionHeader, SAICard, DSColors.textSecondary, DSColors.separator, DSTypography.caption.\n\n## Pattern 5: Calm but High-salience Alarm Active Screen\n- Pattern name: Focused alarm state UI with constrained action surface.\n- Source app or design reference: Challenge alarm competitors with prominent challenge-first interfaces; Apple HIG focus and hierarchy guidance.\n- Why it fits this product: Alarm-active moments are high stress; UI should prioritize one next action, readable status, and no distracting pathways.\n- What to adapt into SwiftUI: Full-screen active state showing current mission, time elapsed, and a single primary action; optional emergency path behind explicit confirmation.\n- What not to copy: Avoid cloning exact color gradients, mascots, or layout scaffolds from incumbents.\n- DesignSystem components or tokens likely to use: SAIGlass, SAIButton, DSTypography.title, DSGradient, DSColors.background, SAIMotion.spring.\n\n## Pattern 6: Consequence Selection Without Shame UI\n- Pattern name: Accountability mode picker for self-commitment, trusted contact, or streak protection.\n- Source app or design reference: Nuj consequence framing and Reddit distrust of invasive social-shaming mechanics.\n- Why it fits this product: Maintains motivational pressure while reducing churn from privacy and social discomfort.\n- What to adapt into SwiftUI: Segmented accountability options with transparent summaries of what happens after a miss and explicit opt-in boundaries.\n- What not to copy: No public leaderboards, manipulative social copy, or coercive contact-import flows.\n- DesignSystem components or tokens likely to use: SAIChip, SAICard, secondary SAIButton, DSColors.accentSecondary, A11y labels.\n\n## Pattern 7: No-ad Morning Path and Value-forward Paywall Timing\n- Pattern name: Interruption-free critical path monetization.\n- Source app or design reference: Reddit and App Store ad-friction complaints; Apple HIG subscription clarity patterns.\n- Why it fits this product: Morning alarm dismissal is the least tolerant moment for monetization friction; trust is a differentiation lever.\n- What to adapt into SwiftUI: Keep active-alarm and immediate post-dismissal surfaces ad-free; present subscription prompts during setup completion or after successful wake streaks.\n- What not to copy: Avoid hard paywalls that block basic alarm reliability and countdown-pressure dark patterns.\n- DesignSystem components or tokens likely to use: SAIGlass paywall CTAs, primary and secondary SAIButton, DSColors.accentPrimary, DSLayout.readableMaxWidth.\n\n## Pattern 8: Template-based Quick Start\n- Pattern name: Persona recipe presets for student, shift worker, chronic snoozer, and parent contexts.\n- Source app or design reference: App Store research recommendation for segment-specific wake recipes; Apple HIG efficiency principle.\n- Why it fits this product: Reduces setup fatigue while mapping to high-variance wake contexts.\n- What to adapt into SwiftUI: First-run template cards with one-tap apply, editable after apply, and visible mission plus check defaults.\n- What not to copy: Do not reuse competitor persona names, illustrations, or category language verbatim.\n- DesignSystem components or tokens likely to use: SAIShowcaseView, SAICard, SAITag, DSSpacing, DSRadius.l, DSColors.surfaceTinted.\n\n## Sources\n- Apple Human Interface Guidelines: https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/\n- Alarmy listing: https://apps.apple.com/us/app/alarmy-alarm-clock-sleep/id1163786766\n- Nuj listing: https://apps.apple.com/us/app/nuj-alarm-clock/id1557053396\n- Challenges Alarm Clock listing: https://apps.apple.com/us/app/challenges-alarm-clock/id1247289889\n- Barcode Alarm Clock listing: https://apps.apple.com/us/app/barcode-alarm-clock/id699437630\n- Existing research artifact: .workflow/iphone-app-factory/research/app-store.md\n- Existing research artifact: .workflow/iphone-app-factory/research/reddit.md\n- Existing research artifact: .workflow/iphone-app-factory/research/competitors.md\n- Local DesignSystem references: apps/waketask-iphone/docs/foundations/DesignSystem.md, apps/waketask-iphone/docs/modules/DesignSystem.md, apps/waketask-iphone/Packages/DesignSystem/README.md\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_14","type":"agent_message","text":"# WakeTask Product Spec Candidate (Model: GPT-5 Codex)\n\n## Problem Statement\nPeople with high-consequence mornings (work/school/caregiving/shift change) do not trust standard alarms to get them fully awake and out of bed. Existing alarm apps are often too easy to dismiss half-asleep, too repetitive, too ad-disruptive at critical moments, and weak at preventing post-dismiss relapse.\n\n## Target User\n- Heavy sleepers and chronic snoozers with real penalties for oversleeping.\n- Users who can dismiss alarms while semi-conscious.\n- Privacy-sensitive users who still want strict wake enforcement.\n- Secondary segments for MVP templates: student, shift worker, parent, chronic snoozer.\n\n## MVP Feature Set\n1. Alarm setup with strictness profile and mission stack template.\n2. Adaptive mission engine (minimum 3 modalities): math, movement, scan/photo verification.\n3. Alarm-active focused UI with constrained actions and explicit emergency path.\n4. Post-dismiss wake contract: timed wake-check with escalation on no response.\n5. Reliability ledger: per-alarm timeline (`scheduled -> fired -> mission -> wake-check -> outcome`) plus failure reason logging.\n6. First-task bridge: one required micro-task after wake verification.\n7. No interstitial ads in alarm-active, dismiss, and wake-check flows.\n8. Weekly wake consistency summary.\n\n## Non-Goals (MVP)\n- Sleep-stage tracking platform or wearable-first sleep analytics.\n- Public social feed/leaderboards.\n- Large wellness content library.\n- Rebuilding core platform infra already provided by SwiftAIBoilerplatePro (auth/payments/network/localization/settings/design system).\n\n## User Journeys\n1. First Run\n- User selects urgency profile/template.\n- App explains reliability model, mission behavior, wake-check, and privacy boundaries.\n- Permissions requested with rationale in context.\n- User creates first alarm in under 2 minutes.\n\n2. Critical Morning\n- Alarm fires into high-salience active screen.\n- User completes adaptive mission stack.\n- App schedules wake-check and requires first micro-task.\n- User reaches completed state with logged evidence.\n\n3. Relapse/Failure\n- User misses wake-check window.\n- Escalation executes per selected mode.\n- Ledger records exact failure path and timestamp.\n\n4. Trust Review\n- User opens reliability timeline for recent alarms.\n- User sees actionable reason codes and adjusts strictness/template.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n1. Alarm Setup\n- User can create/edit/delete alarms with mission stack and strictness.\n- Time-to-first-alarm setup median under 120 seconds in internal test cohort.\n\n2. Mission Engine\n- At least 3 mission types available.\n- Difficulty adjusts based on last 7-day relapse signals.\n- Repeated identical mission sequence avoided across consecutive mornings unless user opts fixed mode.\n\n3. Wake Contract\n- Wake-check is scheduled immediately after dismissal with configurable window.\n- Missed wake-check always triggers configured escalation.\n- Passed wake-check transitions alarm outcome to `verified_awake`.\n\n4. Reliability Ledger\n- Every alarm instance logs lifecycle events with timestamp and outcome.\n- Failure reasons include at minimum: not triggered, dismissed_unverified, wake_check_missed, task_bridge_incomplete.\n- Logs visible in-app and retained locally by default.\n\n5. First-Task Bridge\n- User must define one micro-task (or choose skip globally in settings).\n- Completion state is logged and shown in morning summary.\n\n6. Trust/Monetization\n- No interstitial ads during critical wake path.\n- Paywall prompts only outside critical wake path.\n\n7. Technical/Quality Bar\n- Swift 6 strict concurrency passes build/test.\n- Production and test Swift files remain under 400 lines.\n- SwiftLint, SwiftFormat, Qlty, secret scanning are blocking.\n- `xcodebuild build` and `xcodebuild test` pass in macOS lane.\n\n## Analytics and Events\n- `onboarding_started`\n- `onboarding_completed`\n- `alarm_created`\n- `alarm_fired`\n- `mission_started`\n- `mission_completed`\n- `mission_failed`\n- `alarm_dismiss_attempted`\n- `alarm_dismissed_verified`\n- `wake_check_scheduled`\n- `wake_check_passed`\n- `wake_check_missed`\n- `escalation_triggered`\n- `first_task_started`\n- `first_task_completed`\n- `alarm_outcome_logged`\n- `reliability_ledger_viewed`\n- `strictness_changed`\n- `template_applied`\n- `paywall_viewed_noncritical`\n\nEvent requirements:\n- Include anonymous user id, alarm id, local timestamp, app version, strictness level.\n- No raw photo data or sensitive free-text in analytics payloads.\n\n## Privacy and Security Requirements\n1. Local-first processing for mission validation where feasible; clearly disclose any server-side processing.\n2. Data minimization: store only data needed for alarm reliability, mission outcome, and summaries.\n3. No secret hardcoding; no credential logging; no environment dumps.\n4. Permission just-in-time prompts with explicit purpose copy.\n5. Private accountability only (opt-in trusted contacts), no public shaming mechanics.\n6. User controls for data export/delete and mission-history retention window.\n\n## App Store 4.3 Differentiation Statement\nWakeTask is not a template alarm clone. Its differentiated product loop is:\n- Explainable reliability ledger (auditable alarm evidence),\n- Adaptive anti-autopilot mission sequencing (personalized wake friction),\n- Post-dismiss wake contract with escalation,\n- Wake-to-first-task execution bridge.\nThis shifts category value from “alarm dismissal challenge” to “verified wakefulness and first-action execution,” with a trust-first, ad-free critical path.\n\n## Appium Exploratory Testing Requirements\n1. Automated exploratory tapper must traverse every reachable enabled button/control on iPhone form factors.\n2. Mandatory scenario coverage:\n- First-run onboarding + permission flow.\n- Alarm creation/edit/delete.\n- Alarm-active mission completion paths.\n- Wake-check pass/fail branches with escalation.\n- First-task bridge complete/incomplete branches.\n- Reliability ledger browsing/filtering.\n- Settings/privacy controls.\n3. Capture artifacts: run log, control coverage report, screenshots/video of critical-path screens.\n4. Fail if any reachable enabled control is untappable, crashes, or dead-ends without recovery.\n5. Include evidence in CI artifacts unless explicitly deferred by `allow_macos_deferred`.\n\n## SwiftAIBoilerplatePro Module Reuse Plan\n1. Reuse platform modules as-is:\n- Auth/session, networking, storage, localization, settings, design system, purchase/paywall scaffolding, analytics pipeline.\n2. Implement new WakeTask domain modules:\n- `AlarmDomain` (models/state machine),\n- `MissionEngine` (adaptive challenge selection/scoring),\n- `WakeContract` (wake-check orchestration/escalation),\n- `ReliabilityLedger` (event store + timeline view model),\n- `FirstTaskBridge` (post-wake task workflow).\n3. UI composition with existing DesignSystem components/tokens:\n- `SAICard`, `SAIButton`, `SAIChip`, `SAIListRow`, `SAISectionHeader`, `SAIMotion`.\n4. Architecture:\n- Keep features modular and testable; do not rebuild core infra without ADR.\n- Preserve Swift 6 concurrency correctness across async workflows.\n\n## Definition of Done\n1. Product\n- All MVP acceptance criteria met.\n- Differentiation loop demonstrably functional end-to-end.\n\n2. Engineering\n- Clean modular implementation under file-size constraints.\n- Unit/integration coverage for mission adaptation, wake-check escalation, and ledger correctness.\n\n3. Quality Gates\n- Lint/format/qlty/secret scanning pass.\n- macOS CI `xcodebuild build` and `xcodebuild test` green.\n- Appium exploratory evidence attached with critical-path coverage.\n\n4. Compliance/Release Readiness\n- App Store 4.3 differentiation copy finalized in metadata.\n- Privacy disclosures aligned with actual data flows.\n- TestFlight-ready build produced from `apps/waketask-iphone`."}}
